definition.value: A dihydroxyflavone that is the 5-deoxy-derivative of 4',5,7-trihydroxy-3'-methoxyflavone (chrysoeriol).
Macromolecules composed of repeating substituted or unsubstituted ethylbenzene units.
A polymer composed of repeating ethyl benzene groups.
A macromolecule derived from two or more species of monomer.

A copolymer macromolecule composed of homopolymeric blocks of 1->4-linked homopolymeric blocks of 1->4-linked sodium beta-D-mannuronate and sodium alpha-L-guluronate residues, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks. The sodium salt of alginic acid.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): bulking agent, carrier, emulsifier, foaming agent, gelling agent, glazing agent, humectant, sequestrant, stabilizer, thickener.
Any fatty acid containing at least one C=C double bond.

Any poly(ethylene glycol) derivative composed of PEG-ylated sorbitan [2-(1,2-dihydroxyethyl)tetrahydrofuran-3,4-diol] normally containing a total of 20 oxyethylene groups, with one or more of the terminal hydroxy groups esterified with a fatty acyl group. They are used as emulsifiers and dispersing agents in some pharmaceuticals products and as defoamers and emulsifiers in some foods.
A polymer composed of PEG-ylated sorbitan, where the total number of poly(ethylene glycol) units is 20 (w + x + y + z = 20) and a single terminal is capped by a palmitoyl group.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): dispersing agent, emulsifier.
A polymer composed of PEG-ylated sorbitan, where the total number of poly(ethylene glycol) units is 20 (w + x + y + z = 20) and a single terminal is capped by a dodecanoyl group.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): dispersing agent, emulsifier, stabilizer.
A polymer composed of PEG-ylated sorbitan, where the total number of poly(ethylene glycol) units is 20 (w + x + y + z = 20) and a single terminal is capped by a stearate group.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): dispersing agent, emulsifier.
A polymer composed of PEG-ylated sorbitan, where the total number of poly(ethylene glycol) units is 20 (w + x + y + z = 20) and a single terminal is capped by an oleoyl group.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): dispersing agent, emulsifier, stabilizer.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan compound formed by methylating cellulose through exposure to NaOH/CH3Cl.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): bulking agent, coating agent, emulsifier, glazing agent, stabilizer, thickener.
An icosatrienoic acid having three cis- double bonds at positions 11, 14 and 17.
An icosatrienoic acid having three cis double bonds at positions 8, 11 and 14.
A polymer compose of repeating propane-1,2-diyl units.
A quinoline derivative with a 1,3-dioxoindan-2-yl substituent at C-2.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour.
A thia-alkylglucosinolate that has a 5-(methylsulfanyl)pentyl side chain attached to the sulfonated oxime group.
An alkylglucosinolate that is the conjugate base of glucocapparin.
An alkylglucosinolate that is the conjugate base of glucocochlearin.
A thia-alkylglucosinolate that has a 4-(methylsulfanyl)butyl side chain attached to the sulfonated oxime group.
A thia-alkylglucosinolate resulting from the removal of the proton of the hydrogen sulfate group of glucoiberverin.
An alkenylglucosinolate that is the conjugate base of gluconapin.
A glucosinolate that is glucobrassicanapin which has been hydroxylated at the 3-position of the hex-5-enimidoyl chain.
A aralkylglucosinolate that is the conjugate base of gluconasturtiin.
A alkylglucosinolate that is the conjugate base of glucoputranjivin.
A glucosinolate resulting from the removal of the proton from the oxime hydrogen sulfate group of glucoraphenin.
A benzothiazole consisting of a benzene ring fused to an isothiazole.

An indole alkaloid fundamental parent with a structure of 9H-beta-carboline carrying a methyl substituent at C-1. It has been isolated from the bark of Sickingia rubra, Symplocus racemosa, Passiflora incarnata, Peganum harmala, Banisteriopsis caapi and Tribulus terrestris, as well as from tobacco smoke. It is a specific, reversible inhibitor of monoamine oxidase A.
A compound having the general formula RR'C(OH)OR'' (R'' =/= H).
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
A dicarboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of both carboxylic acid functions of (6R)-5,10-methenyltetrahydrofolic acid.

An optically active cyclic ketone consisting of 3,5,6-trihydroxycyclohexa-2,4-dien-1-one bearing two 3-methylbut-2-en-1-yl substituents at positions 4 and 6 as well as a 3-methylbutanoyl group at the 2-position.
A dimeric hydrolysable tannin in which 2 moles of potentillin monomer are linked via a dehydrogalloyl group; an antitumor tannin of Agrimonia pilosa Ledeb., which induces interleukin-1.
A flavanone glycoside that is hesperitin  having an 2-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety attached to the 7-hydroxy group.
Any fatty acid whose skeletal carbon atoms form an unbranched open chain.
Any salt prepared using acetic acid as the acid component.

A straight-chain, monounsaturated, 16-carbon fatty acid with a trans-double bond at position C-9; the trans-isomer of palmitoleic acid and predominant trans-16:1 isomer in cheeses from goat and ewe milk. Major dietary sources are partly hydrogenated vegetable oils.
Any member of the sub-set of polyunsaturated fatty acid for which there is an absolute dietary requirement.
Any fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.
An iminium ion that is a dark bluish synthetic dye used as a food colouring agent
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour.
Compounds containing one or more phosphoric acid units.
A hydroxyisoflavone that is 6,7-methylenedioxyisoflavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 4'.
Hydroxy boron compounds of general formula BxOyHz.
An organooxygen compound having the structure RR'C(OR'')(OR''') (R'', R''' =/= H). Mixed acetals have R'' and R''' groups which differ.
A hemiacetal having the structure RR(1)C(OH)OR(2) (R, R(1), R(2) =/= H), derived from a ketone by formal addition of an alcohol to the carbonyl group.
